<FIRST>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0582 03-26 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0582,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS Langdon obit; AMs separate on Mufti moved as a0577.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Said Al-Mufti</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Said Al-Mufti, a former Jordanian prime
minister who helped his country become an independent kingdom, died
Saturday, state-run Jordan Television reported.
   The report did not give the cause of death or the age of one of
Jordan's leading citizens throughout the country's 68-year history
as an emirate under British protection and later as an independent
monarchy.
   He served repeatedly in Jordanian cabinets from 1929 until the
early 1960s, often as deputy prime minister and as interior
minister. As prime minister from April to December 1950, Mufti
opposed King Abdullah's negotiations with Israel. He was a major
figure in the regency council that governed Jordan between the
abdication of King Talal in 1952 and the 1953 accession of King
Hussein, then a teen-ager. He served a second term as prime
minister in 1956.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Thomas Langdon</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thomas C. Langdon, 84, a retired editor of
The Pittsburgh Press, died Friday of congestive heart failure and
pneumonia.
   Langdon worked for newspapers in Washington, D.C., Mississippi
and West Virginia before becoming city editor of the McKeesport
(Pa.) Journal in 1925. He later was managing editor of the Journal
before joining the Press in 1926.
   He left the Press after six months to become managing editor of
the Altoona Tribune, but he rejoined the Press in 1929 and stayed
for 40 years.
   Langdon worked on the newspaper's telegraph, city, copy and
features desks and was assistant news editor for 16 years.
</TEXT>
