<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Bhutto-Baby     03-26 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Bhutto-Baby,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bhutto Expecting Second Child</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto, the
first woman to lead a modern Moslem nation, is expecting her second
child in October, family sources said Sunday.
   Ms. Bhutto's first child, a boy named Bilawal, was born last
Sept. 21. A month later, Ms. Bhutto propelled her left-of-center
Pakistan People's Party to a victory in the country's first free
elections in more than a decade.
   The prime minister's marriage in December 1987 was reported to
have been arranged in line with strict Moslem tradition. She
married Asif Zardari, a prominent landowner from Pakistan's western
province of Baluchistan.
   Ms. Bhutto, 35, was pregnant with her first child last year when
Pakistan's military leader, Mohammed Zia ul-Haq, announced
elections.
   Zia overthrew Ms. Bhutto's father, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, in a
bloodless coup in 1977, and Bhutto was convicted of conspiracy to
murder a political rival and executed in 1979.
   Zia died in a plane crash in August. Investigators suspect that
sabotage brought down the plane, but they have never found a
definite cause or suspect.
</TEXT>
