<DOCNO> AP890326-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-26-89 1359EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-PoisonGas     03-26 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poison Gas,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Review Expected to Lead to Tougher U.S. Chemical Export Curbs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is reviewing the need
for tougher U.S. curbs as well as expanded international
cooperation to help block the export to Third World countries of
chemicals and equipment for making poison gas weapons, a Commerce
Department official said Sunday.
   Paul Freedenberg, undersecretary of commerce for export
administration, said the steps could include new legislation or at
least bolstered regulations for enforcing current export control
statutes.
   ``We're reviewing the strengthening of controls,'' he said,
noting that the policy review was being handled primarily by the
State and Commerce departments, with some input from the Central
Intelligence Agency.
   Freedenberg said he expects the review will be completed in the
next few months.
   ``Most likely we won't need legislation, we just need further
regulation,'' he said. ``And more importantly, I think it's likely
that we'll be looking for international cooperation.''
   Freedenberg said the United States and 16 other industrialized
nations have pledged to prevent the export of critical poison-gas
chemicals and manufacturing equipment to four ``problem countries''
_ Iran, Iraq, Libya and Syria.
   But there are other mainly Third World countries, he said, which
are believed to be interested in developing a chemical-weapons
capability.
   ``You have a country such as Egypt _ which is right next door to
Libya and obviously has a concern about Libyan capacity to make
chemical weapons _ where there are no controls whatsoever on that
type of equipment or those chemicals,'' Freedenberg said.
   Other countries which either have poison gas or are developing
the capability of making it include Israel, India, Pakistan, Burma,
North Korea, Taiwan, China and Ethiopia.
   ``If you want to have a comprehensive, worldwide regime, you
have to have a regime that controls both the precursor chemicals
and the equipment to make chemical warfare agents to all the world
outside of the United States and the other 16 members of the
Australia group,'' Freedenberg said.
   The group of industrialized nations is so called because it was
formed at a meeting held at the Australian embassy in Brussels in
1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
