<FIRST>r w AM-PoliticalMoney     03-26 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Political Money,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release at 6:30 p.m. EST - time set by source</HEAD>
<HEAD>GOP Spending Doubled Democrats' in 1987-88 Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   During the 1987-88 election cycle the
Republican Party raised and spent more than double the amount of
money taken in and spent by the Democrats, but the gap between the
two parties' financial strength was less than in 1983-84, the
Federal Election Commission said Sunday.
   A report issued by the commission said the GOP raised $263.3
million and spent $257 million in 1987-88, compared to $127.9
million raised and $121.9 million spent by the Democratic Party.
   By contrast, when President Reagan ran for re-election in
1983-84, the Republicans raised a record $297.9 million and spent
$300.8 million, while the Democrats raised $98.5 million and spent
$97.4 million.
   In 1987-88 the two parties were more closely matched in terms of
so-called coordinated expenditures _ monies spent on behalf of
federal candidates in the general election but not directly
contributed to their campaign coffers. Coordinated expenditures by
the GOP totalled $22.7 million, 27 percent more than the Democrats'
$17.9 million.
   The Democratic Party figure was nearly double the $9 million
spent in coordination with general election campaigns in 1983-84,
while coordinated expenditures by the Republican Party rose only 13
percent from the $20.1 million reported in the earlier two-year
period.
   During the most recent election cycle, direct contributions to
candidates totalled $3.4 million for the Republicans and $1.7
million for the Democrats, the FEC said.
   It reported that of the GOP's total 1987-88 receipts, 87 percent
came from individuals, 3 percent from state and local party
organizations, 1 percent from political action committees, or PACs,
and 9 percent from other sources. For the Democrats, the breakdown
was 68 percent from individuals, 6 percent from state and local
parties, 8 percent from PACs and 17 percent from other sources.
</TEXT>
