<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMER, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sucker Fest 1989 has gone belly-up.
   You say that from the sound of it you won't miss it? But there
would have been fun things to do at the eighth annual festival
scheduled for April 7-9.
   Sucker Fest, named for the freshwater fish found in nearby
Saginaw Bay, has offered events including a chain saw log-cutting
contest and rope crossings of the Rifle River that runs through the
Arenac County community of 403 residents.
   But the City Council in Michigan's self-proclaimed smallest city
voted last week to cancel the event, not for lack of participation
but because it couldn't get insurance.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was a protest to end all protests.
   A group of college students staged a protest for no reason,
holding blank signs and distributing fliers that said nothing. They
insisted nothing was on their minds.
   ``The whole point is there are so many protests that people
don't read the signs and don't care anymore,'' said Bryan Finch,
22, a Cabrillo College student who organized Friday's
``non-protest'' and served as the official ``unspokesperson.''
   He said the group was protesting the trivialization of protests.
   ``People are making them worthless by doing them so much,'' said
Finch.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TIFTON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peanut butter, invented by an anonymous St.
Louis physician as a health food for invalids and later fed to
mental patients, is 99 years old this year and still going strong.
   ``We don't know his name,'' said Marilyne Moore, director of
promotions and education for the Georgia Peanut Commission. ``We
don't know how it came about, other than that he ground up peanuts
to make a health food that they could consume.''
   The process was later patented by the Kellogg family of Battle
Creek, Mich.
   ``Mom and apple pie and peanut butter are a way of life in
America,'' said Don Koehler, the commission's executive director,
noting that Americans consumed about a billion pounds of peanut
butter last year.
   ``We'd like to think that peanut butter may be pushing apple
pie.''
</TEXT>
