<FIRST>u i FewWesternerstoCelebrateEasterinKabul     03-26 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>Few Westerners to Celebrate Easter in Kabul</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Easter, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shortly after sunrise Sunday, about 30
members of the dwindling Western community gathered for an Easter
service at the Italian Embassy, where the only remaining occupants
are a priest and three dogs.
   As rain poured down outside, turning Kabul into a morass of
brown-gray mud, the Rev. Angelo Panigati played a small, table-top
organ and led worshipers through three choruses of ``Christ the
Lord is Risen Today.''
   The congregation of Catholics and Protestants vividly
illustrated the effect of international politics.
   No diplomats were present, only aid workers and some military
men from the United Nations.
   The United States and 11 other countries evacuated their
diplomats two months ago during the final phase of the
now-completed Soviet military withdrawal from Afghanistan.
   Some of those who most wanted the Red Army to leave were the
ones who closed their embassies, professing fears security would
deteriorate rapidly when there were no longer Soviet soldiers in
the streets.
   The United Nations, which sponsored the Geneva accord that led
to the Soviet withdrawal, now is reduced to 23 foreign staffers,
one-fifth the number here eight months ago.
   Easter Sunday's congregation at the barricaded embassy, where
the Italian flag still flies but no business is conducted, was a
representative sample of the fluctuating Western community that
rarely exceeds 150.
   The Roman Catholic Panigati, an Italian citizen who spent the
last 24 years in Kabul teaching Afghan students and ministering to
foreign Christians, does not want to leave.
   ``This is my parish,'' he said, gesturing at worshipers.
   They included Irish and Fijian colonels from the U.N. force
established for the Soviet withdrawal, German nuns and laymen who
nurse in Kabul hospitals, Swiss from the International Committee of
the Red Cross, a Canadian Mennonite who stayed behind to help run
an eye hospital after most of his associates were withdrawn by the
International Assistance Missions, a Protestant aid organization.
   The Afghan government, trying hard but largely without success
to distance itself from its communist coup-installed origins in
1979 and the accompanying political killings, imprisonments and
torture, has harshly attacked the West for leaving Kabul.
   President Najib, a former secret police chief who took power in
1986, says he is ready to share power with the Moslem guerrillas.
   A Foreign Ministry statement Wednesday appealed to the United
States and other nations to reopen their embassies.
   President Najib's government repeatedly has denounced the
embassy closures as a propaganda ploy to destabilize his government
and boost morale of the U.S.-supported guerrillas, who have waged a
decade-old war against the regime.
   The government observes that a bloodbath has not occurred in
Kabul since the Soviet withdrawal was completed Feb. 15. Since
then, days and even weeks have passed without guerrilla rockets
landing in Kabul, compared to the 20 or 30 rockets that were
landing in the capital daily last fall.
   But the war is far from over, as evinced by new fortifications
in Kabul, the Soviet planes that bring missiles and ammunition as
well as food, and the 20-day battle for the eastern city of
Jalalabad, where the government's unverified figures say more than
2,100 people have been killed.
   But war's fears were set aside for a few minutes Easter morning
as Panigati read the story of Christ's resurrection from the Gospel
of Mark and a brown-and-white dog, a refugee from the now-shuttered
French Embassy, chased its tail.
   At the end of the half-hour service, the priest noted that the
work of a few Christians in this war-devastated nation still can
produce good results and he wished for ``peace for the beloved
Afghan people.''
   The last hymn of the Easter service was entitled ``The Strife is
Over.''
</TEXT>
