<FIRST>r a AM-ZZZZBest     03-26 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ZZZZ Best,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former `Whiz Kid' Faces Sentencing On 57-Count Conviction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three months after he was convicted of 57
counts of securities, credit card and mail fraud, a man once
considered a teen-age business genius returns to court Monday to be
sentenced.
   A prosecution sentencing memorandum asked for a sentence of at
least 25 years behind bars for Barry Minkow, saying such a term was
``more than justified'' for the 22-year-old man.
   U.S. District Judge Dickran Tevrizian could sentence Minkow to
up to 300 years. But defense attorney David Kenner has said that is
unlikely, and was expected to argue for a much shorter term than
the government recommendation.
   ``Barry is a young man ...,'' Kenner said after his client was
convicted. ``I would hope Barry will still be a young man when he
is released.''
   Minkow, who was 16 when he launched his ZZZZ Best carpet
cleaning company in his parents' garage, has insisted he was a
captive of mobsters who took over his company and forced him to
commit fraud.
   The government claimed he was a shrewd con man who convinced
Wall Street investors and TV talk show hosts that he was a business
genius.
   ``He sold investors on a business which, for the most part, did
not exist,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney James Asperger who said
Minkow's manipulations cost investors over $25 million.
   The collapse of ZZZZ Best rocked the volatile U.S. money markets
and exposed the vulnerability of major securities firms and banks
which bought Minkow's sales pitch and committed millions to his
company.
   The keystone of Minkow's scheme, devised with a number of
associates, was a claim that ZZZZ Best was making a fortune
restoring water- and fire-damaged buildings. Investors were taken
on tours of alleged restoration projects in abandoned buildings
with which ZZZZ Best had no connection.
   At the height of his fame, Minkow lived in a $1 million house
and drove a Ferrari. But he claimed he actually was living a
nightmare of fear as gangsters moved in on his empire.
   ``I was just a front man for the mob,'' he testified at his
trial. ``I was just a puppet.''
   It became clear at the trial that Minkow had dealings with such
mob figures as the late Jack Catain. The defense presented evidence
that Los Angeles police had investigated mob infiltration of ZZZZ
Best. But the judge limited such testimony and jurors rejected the
claim that Minkow was a hostage of the mob.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
