<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Thatcher     03-26 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Thatcher,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thatcher Going To Africa On Peace Mission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher leaves for Africa
Monday on a tour aides describe as a diplomatic push to launch a
peace initiative in southern Africa, including a political
settlement in South Africa.
   The weeklong trip to Morocco, Zimbabwe and Malawi, with a
stopover in Nigeria, underlines Mrs. Thatcher's transformation from
being in the mid-1980s the focus of African resentment over what
black states see as Western foot-dragging over South African
apartheid.
   ``This is the beginning of an initiative,'' said a senior
British government source, speaking on condition on anonymity.
``But how far it will go is anybody's guess at the moment.''
   Zimbabwe President Robert Mugabe, once an outspoken critic of
Mrs. Thatcher for her refusal to impose tough sanctions against
South Africa, is planning a warm welcome for the British
Conservative Party leader.
   It is her first visit to the former white-ruled Rhodesia, which
Britain steered to independence in 1980, and to Malawi, another
ex-colony.
   South African Foreign Minister Pik Botha, who held a surprise
meeting with Mrs. Thatcher at her invitation in London on March 15,
indicated before the trip that she could play a pivotal role in
southern Africa.
   Con Botha, a spokesman for South Africa's governing National
Party, said in a British Broadcasting Corp. radio interview that
South Africans have ``the highest regard'' for Mrs. Thatcher's
anti-sanctions stance.
   ``We also think she is in a particularly good position to
influence African states she is going to visit now to adopt a more
pragmatic attitude toward developments in southern Africa,'' he
said.
   Mrs. Thatcher may try to build on recent agreements under which
Soviet-supported Cuban troops will withdraw from Angola and
U.N.-supervised elections will bring independence to Namibia.
   In Zimbabwe, Mugabe will likely reiterate demands for Britain to
impose tough embargoes against South Africa, a major trading
partner.
   Talks in Zimbabwe and Malawi are expected to focus on new moves
to end the civil war waged in neighboring Mozambique by Renamo
rebels and on the implementation of the Namibian peace settlement.
   Mrs. Thatcher denied published reports she plans to organize a
southern African regional peace conference, but said Britain will
help if asked.
</TEXT>
