<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-26 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Develop Over Texas And Louisiana, Heavy Rain In Arizona</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Moist air from the Gulf of Mexico fueled thunderstorms Sunday in
the south-central part of the nation and showers on the Plains, and
parts of Arizona got heavy snow or rain.
   Southerly wind brought mild temperatures into much of the
eastern two-thirds of the nation. Fort Wayne, Ind., tied its record
of 75 degrees and Ottumway, Iowa, tied its record of 78. Dodge
City, Kan., hit a non-record 85 degrees.
   Thunderstorms over much of Louisiana and southeastern Texas
produced pea- to marble-size hail at Longview and Talco, Texas, and
Lake Charles, La.
   Wind gusted to 36 mph during a thunderstorm in sections of San
Antonio, Texas, and lightning destroyed a house and damaged another
one in the town of Center, in eastern Texas, the National Weather
Service said.
   Scattered showers extended over eastern Kansas and northern
Missouri. Dodge City, Kan., also had wind gusts to 51 mph.
   Elsewhere, an upper level storm system over southern California
produced showers in sections of the Southwest.
   In Arizona, Phoenix received 1.05 inches of rain during the 24
hours up to 11 a.m. MST. Fountain Hills, Payson and Prescott all
received around 1 1-3 inches of rain during the 24 hours up to 8
a.m. MST.
   Higher elevations of Arizona received heavy snow, including 9
inches overnight at Flagstaff. Light afternoon snow was reported at
Butte, Mont., and Sun Valley, Idaho.
   Afternoon temperatures were in the 70s as far north as the
mid-Atlantic Coast states, the Ohio Valley and the Chicago area,
with some readings in the lower 80s in the Carolinas.
   In contrast, dense fog and temperatures in the 40s prevailed in
northern sections of Michigan, Wisconsin and Minnesota and in North
Dakota.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 34
degrees at Butte, Mont., to 87 at Harlingen, Texas. Sunday's
early-morning low in the Lower 48 states was 14 degrees at Truckee,
Calif.
   For Monday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
across much of the great Plains and Mississippi Valley, and will be
most numerous from Texas across Oklahoma to the middle Mississippi
Valley. Showers were forecast in sections of Arizona and New
Mexico. Widespread rain was forecast in the Pacific Northwest, with
showers extending into Idaho and Montana.
   Highs in the 40s were predicted in North Dakota and sections of
Montana; in the 50s in Maine, northern Michigan and northern
Minnesota, and from the Pacific Northwest to the Rockies; in the
80s in sections of the central Plains, from southern Texas across
the Gulf Coast states to the southern Atlantic Coast states, in
sections of the Tennessee Valley and the southern Appalachians; and
in the 60s and 70s across much of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
