<FIRST>r i AM-SouthKorea     03-26 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Korea,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Mobilizes Thousands of Police To Halt Protests</HEAD>
<UNK>By BARRY RENFREW_ ^Associated Press Writer_</UNK>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government deployed thousands of
riot troops throughout Seoul Sunday in a crackdown on radical
groups to end anti-government demonstrations. Students clashed with
troops in two southern cities.
   Riot squads were posted outside important government buildings
in Seoul and at some major intersections.
   Police declined to say how many troops were deployed, but about
700 riot police in 18 buses were posted at the U.S. Embassy Sunday.
   Roh last week ordered security forces to take tough measures to
halt a wave of protests and break up radical organizations he said
were trying to stage a violent revolution. Radicals have called for
the resignation of Roh, who they say is not committed to genuine
democracy.
   No incidents were reported in Seoul, but radical students
clashed with riot police in the southern provincial cities of
Chonju and Kwangju, according to Yonhap, the national news agency.
   In Chonju, police battled about 600 protesters who hurled
firebombs and rocks after they were blocked from marching out of
Chonbuk University, Yonhap said. In Kwangju, several hundred
students battled police after police stopped them from leaving
Chonam University to support strikers at a shipyard, the report
said.
   About 1,000 dissidents and radical students took part in a
peaceful rally at Korea University in western Seoul to demand Roh's
immediate resignation. Dissident leaders denounced Roh and accused
him of attempting to impose military rule.
   ``We call for the resignation of the Roh Tae-woo regime which
cannot carry out democratic reforms and does not represent the
nation,'' said a declaration by the United National Democratic
Movement, South Korea's main dissident alliance.
   About 2,000 riot police in green combat fatigues and visored
helmets were posted in sidestreets around the campus. The
protesters dispersed peacefully.
   Yonhap also reported that police arrested about 600 students
late Saturday after a violent protest earlier in the day at Yonsei
University in east Seoul. National Police Headquarters said it
could not confirm the report.
   Roh announced March 20 he was indefinitely postponing a promised
referendum on his performance because of disputes over how to hold
the vote and violent protests by radicals.
   The former general called the radicals a threat to political
stability and said they were attempting to stage a leftist
revolution.
   Radicals have mounted a series of violent anti-government
protests, mainly on college campuses, to call for Roh's removal.
But they lack public support because most South Koreans reject
their violent tactics, and are not seen as a serious threat to the
government's hold on power.
   It was not clear if Roh could win a referendum even though his
government has helped introduce broad democratic reforms. Many
South Koreans are critical of Roh for his ties to his former ally
and authoritarian predecessor, former president Chun Doo-hwan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
