<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia     03-26 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Clash with Ethnic Albanians for Fourth Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SLOBODAN LEKIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,000 ethnic Albanians jeered
and threw stones at police in southern Kosovo province Sunday,
Tanjug said. It was the fourth straight day of protests of
constitutional changes they say limit their autonomy.
   The state news agency did not say if there were casualties or
gunfire, both reported in protests Saturday.
   The crowd, gathered outside the Communist Party headquarters,
shouted ``we will give our lives but not the constitution!'' as
truckloads of police approached, Tanjug said. They then scattered
into side streets, hurling bricks and rocks at police, the agency
said.
   Protesters shouted for police to ``set our comrades free,''
Tanjug said.
   The agency said 146 demonstrators were arrested in the past four
days. Most were convicted of ``petty crime'' and immediately
sentenced to up to 60 days in jail.
   Police patrolled the streets of Pristina, the provincial
capital, and Belgrade television showed police checking identity
papers and inspecting cars.
   Fifteen miles away, in the town of Urosevac, the focus of the
past three days of riots, a small group gathered Sunday but was
dispersed by police.
   Ethnic Albanians are protesting the provincial parliament's
approval Thursday of constitutional amendments giving leaders from
the mainly Christian republic of Serbia more power in Kosovo.
   The ammendments go into effect Tuesday after approval by the
parliament in Serbia, the largest of Yugoslavia's six republics.
They give Serbia more power over police and judicial authorities
and allow Serbia to pass amendments affecting Kosovo without
approval of the provincial parliament.
   Serbia's provinces of Kosovo and Vojvodina have enjoyed
considerable autonomy since 1974, but leaders of mainly Christian
Serbia said they needed more control over Kosovo to protect the
Serbian minority from the mainly Moslem ethnic Albanians, who make
up 85 percent of Kosovo's 1.8 million population.
   In an editorial carried by the Albanian state news agency ATA
monitored in Vienna, the Communist Party daily, Zeri I Popullit
condemned the constitutional changes as ``anti-democratic.''
   On Saturday, rioters reportedly shot at police, who used
truncheons and tear gas to disperse more than 3,000 protesters.
Ethnic Albanians also threw stones and bricks at police, broke the
windows of a train at the local station and overturned three cars.
   According to Tanjug, 24 policemen were injured in the three days
of Urosevac riots, two seriously, though it was not known if any
was wounded by gunfire. It was not known how many demonstrators
were hurt, but Tanjug said none had sought medical help at the
local health center.
   The demonstrations rioting goes against a government ban on
public gatherings imposed after protests last month.
</TEXT>
