<HEAD>Small Plane Crashes In State Forest; Four Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A single-engine plane crashed during
rough weather in Pittsfield State Forest, killing all four people
aboard, authorities said Sunday.
   The four-seat Socata TB-10 aircraft, made by the Italian-French
consortium Aerospatiale, was based at Hanscom Field in Bedford. It
was en route to Albany, N.Y., when it crashed in a light drizzle,
according to Federal Aviation Administration spokesman Michael
Ciccarelli.
   The pilot radioed that he was encountering heavy turbulence
shortly before the plane disappeared from radar late Saturday,
authorities said.
   State Trooper Christopher Ware said the four victims were all
from eastern Massachusetts. They were not identified pending
notification of next of kin.
