<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0628 03-26 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0628,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christians Emerge from Bomb Shelters to Celebrate Easter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto BEI1</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 13 grafs to UPDATE with bombardment renewed, power
plant hit. Picks up 15th pvs, ``Patriarch Nasrallah ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christians emerged from underground
shelters Sunday to celebrate Easter in Beirut and its suburbs but
returned after a 12-hour lull in artillery battles ended at
nightfall.
   Syrian troops and allied Druse militiamen pounded east Beirut
and the Christian-held region north of the city with multibarreled
rocket launchers Sunday night, police said.
   Christian army gunners in hills above the capital struck back
with 155mm howitzer barrages, targeting residential neighborhoods
where they claim the Syrians set up rocket-launching batteries.
   Police said two people were killed and 12 wounded in Sunday's
bombardments, which were separated by a 12-hour daytime lull. That
raised the overall toll to 94 killed and 326 wounded since the
latest fighting broke out March 8.
   Residents on both sides of Beirut's dividing Green Line scurried
back to basements and bomb shelters for a fourth straight night as
the thunderous bombardment intensified.
   ``This is Lebanon's brand of Easter fireworks, deadly
fireworks,'' said Nada Akiki, a Christian housewife reached at her
home near the U.S. Embassy compound.
   Police said the power plant feeding Beirut from a Christian
suburb was burning after taking several direct hits. Authorities
started rationing residents to four hours' power a day.
   Gen. Michel Aoun, 53, the Christian army chief who also leads
the Christian cabinet in Lebanon's dual government, accused Syrian
gunners of trying to assassinate him after police reported his
residential palace and Defense Ministry headquarters took at least
1,000 hits overnight Saturday.
   Another 4,000 rounds struck other Christian suburbs, said police.
   They said 1,500 Christian shells struck Beirut's Shiite Moslem
southern slum, Druse-held towns along the Beirut-Damascus highway
and Syrian army positions in eastern Bekaa valley the same night.
   ``This is not going to end. I am sure they're going to fight
again,'' said Ali Kawtharani, 35, a carpenter who took advantage of
Sunday's lull to flee with his wife and four sons. ``We'll be safer
in the south.''
   Several car convoys, roofs loaded with beds and mattresses,
streamed out of the Syrian-policed slums.
   Long queues formed outside supermarkets as others stockpiled
food.
   Patriarch Nasrallah Sfeir, spiritual head of the powerful
Maronite community, asked in his Easter sermon:
   ``How long should we be trapped like herds in shelters with
cannons and multibarreled rocket launchers raining various kinds of
death on us. Is this a way of living?''
   The Islamic orphanage in the Barbir district abutting Beirut's
dividing Green Line said it came under Christian shellfire before
dawn Sunday.
   ``A divine miracle saved our 300 maimed and retarded patients,''
the orphanage's statement said.
   The latest fighting began after Aoun blockaded illegal
militia-run ports that deprive the government of $100 million a
year in tax revenue.
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss' Syrian-backed Cabinet rejected
Aoun's move and in turn blockaded the Christian enclave.
   Lebanon's rival governments emerged when former President Amin
Gemayel appointed Aoun to lead an acting military Cabinet after
parliament failed to choose a successor when Gemayel's term expired
Sept. 22.
   Syria keeps 40,000 troops in Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League
mandate to end the war.
</TEXT>
