<FIRST>r n AM-DoubleTransplant     03-26 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Double Transplant,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nation's First Heart-Pancreas Transplant Performed In Washington</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Silver Spring, Md., man who received what
was believed to be the nation's first successful heart-pancreas
transplant Saturday, could be out of the hospital in a few weeks,
hospital officials said Sunday.
   ``We think his recovery will be quite fast,'' said Dr. Jimmy A.
Light, Washington Hospital Center transplantation services
director. ``If his recovery is uncomplicated, we expect he will be
discharged within two or three weeks,''
   Barry Katz, 45, a senior scientist for the Strategic Defense
Initiative program, was a severe diabetic whose heart had been
damaged by the disease to the point that it no longer functioned
properly.
   ``This is a young man whose heart was basically destroyed by 25
years of diabetes but was basically healthy otherwise,'' Light
said. ``He was a very good candidate for a heart transplant.''
   Diabetes causes the pancreas to stop producing insulin, a
hormone that regulates the metabolism of sugar in the body. Doctors
decided that Katz's diabetes was so severe that complications would
result if only his heart were replaced.
   Katz was admitted to the hospital Friday. Hospital officials
said he was within days of death, and they decided to do both
transplants on Saturday.
   The Hospital Center proceeded with the operation although it
lacked official permission to perform pancreas transplants from the
district's State Health Planning and Development Agency. That
agency must approve new services and technology offered by local
hospitals.
   Hospital spokeswoman Clare Fiore said the hospital filed an
emergency application with the city last week to do pancreas
transplants, but had yet received no official approval, The
Washington Post reported. Fiore said if the hospital had waited,
Katz would have died.
</TEXT>
