<FIRST>r i AM-India-Nepal     03-26 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Nepal,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>India and Nepal Disagree Over Trade and Transit Treaties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India and Nepal on Sunday failed to
agree on new trade and transit treaties, Indian officials said,
raising fears the landlocked Himalayan kingdom may face shortages
of food and gasoline.
   The trade treaty expired a year ago and India terminated its
provisions Thursday, said the officials on condition of anonymity.
   A separate transit agreement expired Thursday, even though
Nepalese authorities had asked India to continue its provisions
until a new arrangement was signed, officials said.
   India closed 13 of the 15 customs check points along the
country's 1,090- mile border with Nepal after the treaties
terminated, Foreign Ministry spokesman Aftab Seth told reporters.
   The officials also said the Indian government imposed customs
duties on all goods exported from India to Nepal. Under the transit
treaty, India had allowed free access for overland transportation
of goods imported and exported by Nepal.
   Most of Nepal's foreign trade is either with India or conducted
through India, and border closings could lead to food and fuel
shortages.
   Nepal's foreign minister, Shailendra Kumar Upadhaya, met his
Indian counterpart, P.V. Narasimha Rao, in New Delhi on Sunday.
Sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the ministers
failed to reach an agreement.
   Seth said the two sides agreed to discuss the issue at a later,
unspecified time.
   Officials said Rao rejected a Nepalese proposal that the trade
and transit treaties should be negotiated jointly and not
separately, as India had suggested.
   India and Nepal have enjoyed friendly relations for decades.
There are no restrictions on travel between the neighbors.
   But reports from Katmandu said India was increasingly concerned
over Nepal's expanding relations with China. India fought a border
war with China in 1962 and since then, relations between the two
nations have remained uneasy.
   In August, Nepal reportedly bought unspecified Chinese arms for
its 30,000-strong armed forces.
</TEXT>
