<FIRST>r a AM-AntiqueDesk     03-26 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Antique Desk,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicholas Brown's Desk Expected To Sell For New Record</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mahogany desk once owned by the
namesake of Brown University is expected to fetch a record price at
auction this summer, surpassing the $2.9 million sale of Marie
Antoinette's console table.
   Nicholas Brown's former desk-bookcase, which stands 9 feet, 5
inches tall, is expected to sell for more than $3 million at
Christie's in New York on June 3, according to antique experts.
   Marie Antoinette's console table was sold at Sotheby's in London
last November.
   ``There's never been anything like it on the market,'' Eddy
Nicholson, a New Hampshire collector, told Art &amp; Antiques magazine.
Thought to have been built in the 1760s, the desk is believed to be
one of 11 of its kind made by Newport cabinetmaker John Goddard.
Nine others survive.
   When Brown, the eldest of four brothers who made their fortunes
in shipping and manufacturing, died in 1791, the desk was the most
valuable object listed in his estate.
   His great-great-great grandson, retired Navy Capt. Nicholas
Brown, remembers the desk as ``the imposing artifact that
symbolized our inheritance.'' Every afternoon, he recalled, his
father would assemble the family in the study to have tea ``in the
shadow of that desk.''
   Brown, executive director of the National Aquarium in Baltimore,
has donated the desk to raise money to save a Providence mansion
purchased by his great-great grandfather in 1814.
   ``One icon is saving the other,'' Brown said.
   Christoper Monkhouse, curator of decorative arts at the Rhode
Island School of Design Museum, said such desks were considered
status symbols.
   ``It was a very political piece _ a way of telling your peers
who you were,'' he said.
   Brown University was named after the original Nicholas Brown,
whose father and uncles had been also been patrons of the
institution.
</TEXT>
