<SECOND>AM-Yeltsin, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0624,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeltsin, In Comeback Bid, Expresses Concern About Election Fairness</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with early, unofficial returns.
Pickup 5th graf pvs: `Large pro-Yeltsin...' ^With AM-Soviet-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boris N. Yeltsin, the fallen protege of President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev, led his rival for parliament by a margin of
more than 7.5-to-1 in early, unofficial returns in Sunday's voting.
   Unofficial returns from three districts of the citywide Moscow
vote had Yeltsin ahead with 4,069 votes to 532 for Yevgeny Brakov,
director of the factory that makes ZIL limousines _ one of the
flashiest symbols of Soviet privilege, which Yeltsin targeted in
his campaign.
   Certified returns for the voting in Moscow would be made public
Monday night, said Nikolai N. Isaeev, spokesman for the Central
Election Commission.
   Yeltsin suggested earlier in the day that the Communist Party
might cheat him out of his political comeback by rigging the vote
count.
   Of more than 2,000 Soviets interviewed at polling places after
voting, 1,734 were for Yeltsin and 162 for Brakov. Others either
refused to disclose how they voted or expressed opposition to
either candidate.
   The informal poll, conducted by Western correspondents, was not
a scientifically accurate indicator of the outcome. But it
supported Yeltsin's claim to widespread popular support, which has
surfaced increasingly toward the end of the first seriously
contested political race in the Soviet capital at least since the
days of Lenin.
   Yeltsin's backers predicted he would win the support of 5
million of Moscow's 6.7 million eligible voters. Yeltsin himself
predicted victory but declined to specify a margin.
   Large pro-Yeltsin rallies were held in the capital in the
closing days of the campaign for the new 2,250 Congress of People's
Deputies, the first seriously contested open political race in
Moscow since the days of Lenin.
   ``People are worried about the election results, worried that
there will be deviations at election stations during vote
counting,'' Yeltsin told reporters after voting Sunday.
``Everything is troubling them.''
   ``Democracy depends on the election procedure, which hasn't been
tested yet,'' he said.
   Yeltsin, 58, who headed Moscow's powerful Communist Party
bureaucracy and held non-voting membership on the ruling Politburo
before his ouster, claims the party worked against his campaign.
   He accused party officials of restricting public access to his
campaign speeches and said they tried to damage his election
chances by setting up a commission in the final weeks of the
campaign to investigate his conduct.
   Yeltsin has demanded an end to special privileges for party and
government officials, such as access to special stores and
chauffeured luxury cars. He also has called for more radical
economic reforms to fill empty store shelves.
   Brakov, 51, has said his top priority is to end food shortages
by providing more machinery to farmers and improving storage and
processing facilities.
   When Yeltin was asked if he was satisfied with his campaign for
Moscow's at-large seat in the new congress, he said Sunday:
   ``Not in its entirety. Maybe it's because there are things we're
not used to. This leap to democracy had some positive and negative
processes.''
   The election campaign, he said, was ``not fully democratic'' but
was a ``big step forward'' from previous balloting in which only
one candidate was put forward for each post. But the real test of
democracy will be whether the vote count is fair, Yeltsin said.
   Gorbachev, who brought Yeltsin into the leadership in 1985 and
two years later oversaw his ouster on charges of making political
mistakes and displaying personal ambition, said criticism of party
officials is normal during campaigns and that Yeltsin was not the
only one who received it.
</TEXT>
