<HEAD>Poll Shows Heath Leading Long in Tuesday's Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WAYNE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A poll shows Republican Dan Heath with a
narrow lead over Democrat Jill Long in the race to fill the
congressional seat once held by Vice President Dan Quayle. The
election is Tuesday.
   In a telephone survey of 1,019 registered voters in the 4th
Congressional District, Heath was favored by 44 percent to 36
percent for Long. About 20 percent were undecided.
   The House seat became vacant when Republican Dan Coats was
appointed to replace Quayle in the Senate. Coats had beaten Long, a
36-year-old business teacher at Indiana University-Purdue
University, by a 62-38 percent margin in the November election.
Heath, 36, is a former congressional aide to Coats.
   The campaign has received close attention from the congressional
campaign committees of both parties. Republicans have been intent
on keeping the seat in GOP control, while Gov. Evan Bayh has been
among those campaigning for Long in hopes of picking up an
additional Demcratic seat in the House.
   The poll was conducted March 19-22 for The Journal-Gazette of
Fort Wayne. It has a margin of effort of plus or minus 3 percentage
points.
