<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Flight103     03-26 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Flight 103,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cabin Crews Oppose Armed Guards On Aircraft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Permitting guards to carry loaded weapons on
aircraft will not deter terrorists but could endanger the planes
and passengers, a trade union representing airline cabin crews said
Sunday.
   The Observer newspaper reported Sunday that police officers
escorting top politicians and members of the royal family are being
allowed to carry loaded guns onto British aircraft under security
regulations revised after the bombing of Pan Am Flight 103.
   Security personnel have been permitted to carry only unloaded
firearms onto aircraft.
   ``The problem is that indiscriminate firing of guns, which could
always occur, could create as much damage as anything else,'' said
George Ryde, national secretary of the Transport and General
Workers Union's civil aviation group.
   The Transport Department said Sunday it would not discuss
security matters. The Civil Aviation Authority declined comment and
Scotland Yard said it had ``no knowledge'' of the matter.
   British Airways, which the Observer identified as one of several
airlines affected by the new order, also said it could not comment.
   Ryde said armed guards on aircraft would do little to deter
terrorists.
   ``If the glass or shell of an aircraft is punctured, it could
cause decompression with people being sucked out,'' he said.
   ``What could an armed guard have done to prevent what happened
at Lockerbie?'' he asked.
   Investigators have said a bomb caused Flight 103 to explode in
midair over Lockerbie, Scotland, on Dec. 21, killing all 259 people
on board and another 11 on the ground. The bomb was contained in a
radio-cassette player in the baggage hold, they said.
   The Sunday Times of London reported an extremist Palestinian
faction funded by Iranian radicals was responsible for the bombing,
and that U.S. intelligence officials know where the bombers are.
   The newspaper, quoting unidentified sources in Washington,
reported that the Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine-General Command made and planted the bomb on behalf of
Iranians seeking revenge for the U.S. Navy downing of an Iranian
jetliner over the Persian Gulf last summer. All 290 people on board
the Iranian plane were killed.
   The newspaper quoted one source as saying the group was paid 10
million dollars to destroy the New York-bound jumbo jet.
   The PFLP is led by Ahmed Jibril, a Palestine Liberation
Organization renegade who opposes PLO chief Yasser Arafat's current
drive for peace negotiations with Israel.
   U.S. National security adviser Brent Scowcroft Sunday denied the
report. Appearing on CBS' ``Face the Nation,'' Scowcroft said, ``We
are not that far along'' in the investigation.
   ``As far as I know, we are narrowing it down significantly, but
I don't know that there is a resolution,'' he said.
   The Observer said the new Civil Aviation Authority regulation
reads: ``Firearms may be loaded when retained by police officers in
the passenger cabin of an aircraft.''
   The newspaper said the regulation was in a leaked copy of a
``restricted'' report on Flight 103 by the government's National
Aviation Security Committee.
   Ryde, a member of the committee, said armed police were not
discussed when the committee held a crisis meeting in January, or
at a regularly scheduled meeting in February. He said he had not
seen the report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890326-0074 </DOCNO>
