<HEAD>Police Say Man Who Crashed Into Pathmark Won't Face Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST ORANGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elderly man who blacked out and
drove his car through a supermarket window, injuring at least 10
people, will not face any charges, police said Sunday.
   West Orange Police Chief Edward M. Palardy said Wolodymyr
Szpyrka, 80, will probably be asked to take another driver's test
and submit to a medical exam.
   ``There will be no criminal charges,'' Palardy said. ``As far as
civil, that's always possible in any accident.''
   Palardy said Szpyrka apparently lost control of his four-door
Buick after blacking out Saturday. The car jumped the sidewalk and
crashed through the plate glass windows of a Pathmark store,
halting against a cash register.
   Police said at least two cashiers and a half-dozen customers
were injured, along with Szpyrka and his wife Ewhenia, 70, who was
also riding in the car.
   Patrolman Dennis Walczak said all the injured were treated at
area hospitals and released.
   One of the most seriously injured, store cashier Marie Elmera,
30, of East Orange, was released from University Hospital in
Newark, nurse Regina Koeppel said. Ms. Elmera sustained back and
internal injuries.
   Police mechanics will probably examine the car Monday to see if
mechanical problems may have contributed to the accident, Palardy
said.
