<SECOND>AM-Plane Crash,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Foreign Students Die in Crash of Small Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A single-engine plane crashed into a
forested mountainside in turbulent weather, killing four foreign
students aboard, authorities said.
   The plane, a four-seat Socata TB-10, was en route from Bedford,
Mass., to Albany, N.Y., when it crashed Saturday night into the
eastern slope of the Berkshire Mountains' Taconic Range,
authorities said.
   Dr. Jeffrey Ross, a Berkshire County medical examiner, said the
three men and a woman were studying in the Boston area and were
from Latin America, Indonesia and Africa.
   ``Because of those backgrounds, it's taking us some time to get
word to their families,'' said Ross, who said he could not release
details of the victims' identities until relatives were notified.
   Although the weather at the time was described as a light
drizzle, the pilot radioed that he was encountering heavy
turbulence shortly before the plane disappeared from radar screens
at about 10:30 p.m.
   ``It appears that they had no prior warning that they were going
into a mountain,'' Major Jim Mackey of the Massachusetts Civil Air
Patrol told a Boston television station.
   The Federal Aviation Administration was investigating the
incident.
