<BYLINE>By A.J. HOSTETLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mob of about 50 people attacked five
police officers making an arrest Sunday, causing several minor
injuries, authorities said.
   The officers were responding to a report about a man armed with
a gun on a street in north Philadelphia shortly after 1 p.m.,
according to Lt. John Walsh. When police arrived to investigate, a
man fitting the description in the report punched two officers.
   About 50 people gathered while police handcuffed the man, Walsh
said. When the officers tried to get him into a police vehicle, a
second man attacked the officers and others in the crowd shoved the
five, he said.
   Police said they arrested cousins James Crawford, 22, and
Maurice Crawford, 19, on charges of assault, risking a riot and
resisting arrest.
   Walsh said no gun was found.
   A sister of James Crawford, Alicia Roberts, gave a different
account of the confrontation.
   She said her brother had been fighting with his girlfriend but
the argument ended before police arrived. James Crawford denied to
the officers that he had a gun but handed over a knife he was
carrying, Ms. Roberts said.
   She said the officers began pushing Crawford, bringing a protest
from their mother, Joanne White. At that point, Ms. Roberts said,
the officers started beating her brother with nightsticks and then
turned on Ms. Roberts and Ms. White.
   Ms. Roberts said she received five stitches to close a head
wound.
   Police declined to comment on Ms. Roberts' account. Walsh said
the five officers were treated for minor injuries at Hahnemann
Hospital. But hospital spokeswoman Linda Clossey said only two
officers were treated for head and knee injuries and released.
   According to Walsh, the first man in the altercation was treated
at St. Joseph's Hospital. A nursing supervisor there, who would not
give her name, said a man named Anthony White and a mother and
daughter she did not identify were treated and released for minor
injuries they received in the confrontation.
