<FIRST>r f AM-TakeoverComputer Bjt   03-26 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Takeover Computer, Bjt,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Electric Teaches Computer To Keep An Eye On Takeovers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Scisor is cq throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Takeover strategists, take note: Your future
competition may have more in common with R2-D2 than with T. Boone
Pickens and Carl Icahn.
   General Electric Co. says it has taught a computer to keep track
of mergers and acquisitions by reading the Dow Jones news service
ticker.
   The finance-minded software package, called Scisor, was created
by the wife-and-husband team of Lisa F. Rau and Paul S. Jacobs at
GE's Research and Development Center in Schenectady, N.Y.
   The prototype software could be adapted to ``almost any area in
which human beings under intense deadline pressure have to struggle
through smothering amounts of paperwork,'' GE said in an
announcement for release Monday.
   Users can ask the computer questions in simple English and get
answers back the same way, GE said, giving this example:
   User: Who received an offer from Bethlehem Steel?
   System: Bethlehem Steel took over Rail Mill.
   The colorless language and relatively limited vocabulary of the
Dow Jones wire made it ideal for experimentation, Ms. Rau said in
an interview last week. Scisor did have some trouble at first with
``sweetened'' bids and ``tender'' offers, she said.
   ``It's not reasoning with the information. It's simply taking
the facts in a story and putting them down. It doesn't know if
something is true or false or reasonable or unreasonable,'' she
said.
   The Dow Jones wire, also called the ``ticker,'' contains
boiled-down company announcements, corporate earnings reports,
government actions affecting business and other information of
interest to the investment community. The wire, a fixture in
investment houses, is part of Dow Jones &amp; Co. Inc., the publisher
of the Wall Street Journal.
   GE's own Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. brokerage unit is interested in
Scisor and will be given a demonstration in coming weeks. But GE
spokesman Peter Gwynne said it may be one or two years before any
part of GE begins offering a Scisor-based product.
   The text enters the computer electronically and the user
communicates with the machine through a keyboard. It has a
vocabulary of about 10,000 words.
   The system figures out a text by diagramming sentences in the
manner of junior high school English classes. It extracts
additional sense by using programmed-in expectations _ for example,
that the bigger company is usually the acquiring one.
   Ms. Rau said some financial people who have seen Scisor in
action are surprised how well it does.
   ``In the distant future, we can imagine the computer not as a
static repository of information but as a librarian who not only
knows where all the information in the library is kept, but also
has read and understood everything in the library,'' Ms. Rau said
in the written announcement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
