<DOCNO> AP890326-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-26-89 1535EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-PhoenixTransit 1stLd-Writethru f0022 03-26 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Phoenix Transit, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0022,0679</SECOND>
<HEAD>Multibillion-Dollar Transit System Up For Vote In Congested City</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Trolley Comeback, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Response to ...,' to CORRECT to half-penny sted
penny tax. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEL REISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters in Phoenix and its suburbs decide Tuesday
whether to add a half-penny to their sales tax to finance an $8.4
billion highway and transit program, including a controversial
103-mile elevated railway.
   The metropolitan area of 2 million people is the nation's
largest without an integrated freeway system. A vast grid of
north-south, east-west streets is stamped across the desert,
relieved only by two Interstate highways and a piece of state
freeway.
   Maricopa County residents are saddled with some of the highest
auto-insurance rates in the nation partly because of intersection
collisions.
   ``The population of this valley is going to double in the
future, whether we like it or not,'' says Herb Drinkwater, mayor of
the wealthy suburb of Scottsdale. ``I've been here 43 years, and I
don't always like it, but we have to deal with it, and there's no
way that there can be enough roads built to handle the traffic.
   ``We've got to get out of our cars and get them off the road.''
   Response to Proposition 300 and its addition of a half-penny to
the 6-cent sales tax is mixed. Neighborhood preservationists and
tax-dollar watchers have lined up against it while expansionists in
the metropolitan area called the Valley of the Sun back it.
   The ambitiousness of the ValTrans proposition can be read in its
statistics _ expansion of the bus system from 350 vehicles to
1,500, running longer expanded hours; 23 miles of commuter rail; 27
miles of rapid-transit bus routes; and the 103 miles of automated
rapid-transit rail lines.
   Cost estimates range from $8.4 billion to $10.4 billion by the
year 2019, but proponents call it about $44 annually for an average
household.
   Moreover, they say, the system will create 7,000 jobs and will
help clean the air over the valley.
   Air travelers approaching the city may be surprised by a brown
haze obscuring nearby mountains. The metropolitan area has just
gone through a voluntary program to cut down on car use and other
pollution causes. A new state law requires that gasoline be blended
with oxygen additives, similar to a program in Denver, six months
of the year to cut pollution.
   Drinkwater said the arguments against ValTrans were put forth 25
years ago against creation of a freeway system. That successful
fight against unified freeway planning led the current chaotic
state of driving here, he said.
   The only operating freeways in the metropolitan area are
Interstate 10, which comes in from the west and bends southeastward
toward Tucson; Interstate 17, which splits off I-10 and heads north
to Flagstaff; and State Route 360, the Superstition Freeway, which
extends eastward from I-10 in Mesa.
   About 100 miles south, I-10 is the only freeway in Tucson. But
while that Pima County seat has only about one-third as many people
as greater Phoenix, a coalition recently unveiled plans for a 1
percent sales-tax hike to raise $6.8 billion for transportation and
other improvements there.
   The rail system is the sticking point for most ValTrans
opponents.
   ``We agree that there are traffic-congestion problems,'' says
George Chasse, chairman of Voters Against Senseless Transit. ``VAST
is not against mass transit but against the part of Proposition 300
that includes 103 miles of light rail.''
   He and others said they doubt that Arizonans, accustomed to the
California-pioneered style of suburban sprawl and freeway driving,
would ever take a train to work.
   However, Ben Greenfield, an insurance agent in Scottsdale, said
residents might welcome a chance to use alternative transportation.
   ``As an individual, I think it's a good idea for the greater
good of everybody,'' Greenfield said. ``If it eliminates some of
the cars and gets some order to this thing, it's a good idea.''
</TEXT>
